This action contributes to the original initiative EUTF-IOM initiative for migrant protection and reintegration in Africa. The initiative covers 14 countries and is made up of specific actions in the 14 countries where it will be implemented. The activities will therefore be mainly implemented at national level but will be coordinated at the regional level in order to ensure harmonization of activities in the different countries and to ensure coherence of the initiative.

This project will enable the first stage implementation of the new national immigration service strategy by equipping and supporting five state command offices with a personnel training and resource centre, as envisioned and defined in the strategy, to begin serving that command’s personnel with newly-designed and highly focused short training programmes (averaging four days), supported by the local training focal point serving as a facilitator, and by providing tailored complementing self-directed learning materials and resources – including computer-based curricula.

This project regulates what services IOM provides to persons who have the right to stay in Switzerland and have been considered eligible by SEM to bring their family members to Switzerland. IOM will carry out pre-departure “fitness to travel” health assessments, transportation services as well as other services related to family reunification as required by the SEM and agreed upon by IOM.

The project provides social support for reintegration to vulnerable migrants for up to six months from the date of their return to Mauritius, through the provision (grants) of material or financial aid, enabling beneficiaries to face basic expenses upon return. Those grants are subject to eligibility criteria and allocated by Office Francais de l'Immigration et de l'Integration.

The project aims at contributing to the sustainable reintegration in their countries of origin of returnees from Switzerland. Possibilities of reintegration assistance may range from professional reintegration (income-generating activity), housing assistance, training/education, cash for care, cash for shelter with potential additional medical assistance.

The project is implementing the ARISE campaign in Tunisia, in collaboration with Pontes RI, an NGO based in Italy and Tunisia, which will be in charge of rolling out the campaign based on the results of a preparatory research focusing on the main profile of potential migrants. This project will contribute to raise awareness of around 3 million people in risks related to irregular migration during the journey and debunk myths about irregular migration, and to provide alternatives solutions.
The overall goal of this project is to contribute to Indonesia's efforts to reduce vulnerability and enhance the resilience of communities to natural disasters.

The eleventh IOM summer school on migration studies will be held in Prague, Charles University, from August 26th to 31st 2019. The program is open for university students (both graduate and undergraduate) as well as young professionals. Six days of lectures, workshops and discussions with experts will be unique opportunity to get familiar with different migration topics: migration and development, integration of migrants, trafficking in human beings, environmental migration, migration and gender and others.

The Middle East Response (MER) Phase 2 is a multi-country three-year project supported by the Global Fund aiming to deliver continuum of care in challenging operating environments, through provision of essential HIV, tuberculosis and malaria services which is essentially the continuation of its preceding project, MER Phase 1 which was implemented in 2017-2018. The interventions are planned towards addressing the needs of general populations with focus on vulnerable groups including refugees, migrants and internally displaced people and people in hard-to-reach areas in Syria, Yemen and Iraq. It also includes Syrian refugees, migrants and vulnerable populations in Jordan and Lebanon where the latter is expanded to Palestine refugees.

The Belgian assisted voluntary return and reintegration programme, known as REAB, has been implemented since 1984, including a reintegration component since 2006. As part of this programme, IOM supports the institutions responsible for implementing the Belgian policy for migration management through the facilitation of safe and dignified returns as well as contributing towards the sustainable reintegration of migrants in their countries of origin.
